No wonder that there are also natural and loyal employer-worker relationships.
Arch.Design thus joined the Czech companies, who offer significant benefits when recruiting new employees, are family-friendly and, through such programs, strengthen their personal marketing.
A bone house also fascinates after 100 years. Look at Gaudi interiors
The roof mutes on like the back of a prehistoric axe, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are shattered fish mills.
This is the Casa Batlló of Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
From the local residents the house with its organic forms got the nickname "Knochenhaus".
Organic shapes, wild colours, the unusual use of stones, splashes and mosaiks, the sloping facades and all present soft lines, all these are typical features for the youth style of Antonio Gaudi.
The facade of the house plays with dreamy lines, tender colors and textures that remind of nature and living creatures.
Only when you look more closely, you can see that everything is controlled by geometry, rhythm and thoughtful order.
In the night the entire façade works even more plastic, more dramatic and the special lighting enhances the brightness of the colours.
The same swinging lines and swallowed shapes also dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-shaped wood copies the window frames, curtains, ornamental elements of doors, even eyeholes and ropes.
The house Batlló in the Eixample district on the lively shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43 was created by the construction of a house from 1877, which was executed by architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on the demolition of the old and the construction of a completely new building, but finally he agreed to Gaudí's idea of an unusual and even cheaper conversion.
However, the Casa Batlló rental house did not design Antoni Gaudí alone.
He worked with architect Josep Maria Jujol.
On its rearboard the decorations for the representative apartment of the reality owner and also the use of mosaics on the façade were his idea.
However, many other artists and artists were also involved in the design of the façade.
The joint work on the drafts for the Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful cooperation between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí's house Casa Milá in the park Güell, where other works of Antoni Gaudí are also located.
Shortly after its completion, the house was received by the local inhabitants of its organic forms because of the nickname "Knochenhaus".
Others, in turn, called it the special window opening mechanism due to the "containing house".
It is also said that the sword of Saint Georg, the Patron of Catalonia, is represented right above the building.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motives.
Gaudí designed for the house a central heating system unique to then with ventilation channels and typical cammies.
Something bizarre already mutates their 45 degree inclination.
In his creation Gaudí consistently ignored all the construction regulations of the time and couldn't be stumbled by them.
Before the start of the construction, he obtained the corresponding building permit from the city, but the information he had given on the planned reconstruction was so vague that the city fathers were so dismayed two years later at the completion that they required remedy.
The councillors were also faced with the fact that the construction with its pillars even intervened in the public staircase.
However, no further changes were made, on the contrary - only fifteen days after the request from the district in this regard, Josep Batlló submitted an application for approval of the two highest floors of the house - and it was granted to him promptly.
The house owner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a social hall, on the third floor the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey building passes a staircase up to the roof terrace.
Through the basic elements of the conversion, all the right angles and straight lines were removed and replaced by curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept of interconnection of rooms.
The social part can be completely linked by opening the salons and thus a larger society could easily talk without having to give up a certain intimacy in more confidential conversations.
The house was rebuilt by Gaudí in addition to a new façade, and received a rather unusual roof and two other floors.
Gaudí's game is also impressive with the light as well as the blue and white glassed tiles with which the courtyard is dressed and the lighthouses.
The game of these two colors gives a maximum amount of light to all the floors of the house.
He simply made use of the principle that white reflects the light better than dark colours that absorb the sunlight on the contrary.
The House Casa Batlló, which was included in 2005 on the UNESCO World Heritage List, can visit everyone today.
On the first floor the spaciousest and most beautiful apartment is made available to the public.
The houseowners only decided to take this step in the year, on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous Creator.
When it was found that this was a fairly viable business, the visits were kept, and they were also extended to other common and the rooftop rooms, including the roof terrace.
However, the price for the visit of the monument is not a cardboard, it is 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist certificates receive a 20% discount.
This amount exceeds the entry prices to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
Anyone who wants to meet the real atmosphere of the house with his dragon towers should try to close friendship with one of the residents and visit him at home.
