A longer finger than a ring finger means a lower risk of cancer
Men whose fingers are longer than the finger of the ring, are apparently at a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising result of a study published by the British Journal of Cancer on Wednesday.
This is supposed to be related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer, especially in men up to sixty," said the co-author of the study, Ros Eeles, Professor at the Institute of Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could thus help to determine which men should be subjected to a prostate cancer test, especially when there are genetic risks or other risk factors, such as family health stress, added Mrs Eeles.
During the period 1994-2009, she and her colleagues in the UK pursued more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer, but at the same time also 3000 healthy men.
With more than half of the participants in the study, the point finger was shorter in the right hand than the ring finger.
For these men, the likelihood of prostate cancer was the same as for 19 percent of those men whose ring and point fingers were the same.
However, in men whose fingers were longer than the finger of the ring, this risk fell by 33 percent, and in men up to 60 by 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two mentioned fingers, which are already prenatal, apparently reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the child was exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer finger.
Earlier research has shown that testosterone is precisely an accelerator of the growth of prostate cancer.
Václav Pačes, the leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, said that this study was volatilely known to him, yet he did not consider the relationship between the length of the finger and the risk of cancer to date to be "offensive".
