The first is a strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the south should leave the euro area.
The second: The reintroduction of German Mark - although it sounds more like science fiction at the moment - is supported by a majority of public opinion, about 50 percent of the population.
Thirdly, a reform of the euro in accordance with German proposals, which means: more macro-economic control; strict budgetary management; penalties for countries that fail to comply with the requirements; possibly the termination of payments in some countries and the extension of the costs of potential adjustment measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been marked for some time, so there are no excuses now.
