Sports and circumvention
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against the Ajax show invention spirit, but not the will to circumvent a sanction.
The alleged exclusion of two players from Real Madrid (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the 23rd November game against the Ajax in the Champions League led to a lot of ink being shed on whether it was a sporty act or not and whether both players should be sanctioned by the UEFA.
As is generally known, the two players lost a few minutes before playing (her team had already clearly won) time and played several fouls so that the arbitrator showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since the Real Madrid would lead its group, the two players will meet the required sanctions in the next league game against the Auxerre and thus enter the next game without cards.
Finally, the UEFA disciplinary committee punished the club trainer José Mourinho with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
Provocation of a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is more common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the Ethos - the unwritten rules but followed in this sport.
Part of the debate on the case presented is based on the fact that a team of the football club Real Madrid (which in his hymn has presented nobleness and honour and had punished its players for similar incidents on other occasions) played the main role in this process, and on the dramatization by Mourinho, which has added a more episode to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate turns about whether this non-expressly banned behaviour is contrary to the principles of sport, that is, whether these acts constitute a circumvention. In fact, this approach is consistent with the rules of sport, but it seems to be circumventing its meaning.
In this case, the damage caused to the sporting spirit should be investigated.
The sports spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not jeopardized by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to avoid that the opposing players benefit unjustifiedly from the counter team. Nor did that happen.
The paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not correspond to what we normally understand by misplay or circumvention, because the circumvention of the rule has not been carried out secretly in order to avoid a sanction, but it should be as noticeable as possible so that it is punished by the arbitrator.
The players waited down and accepted the sanction joyfully.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders took from the intentional fouls.
It should be emphasised here that the rival has not been brought into a more disadvantaged situation or benefits for the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that the team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also no useful strategy for the next game, because the club does not have these players.
The advantage is obviously that the players start the next game phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it is a long-term, up to a certain degree unconscious advantage, as the team could eventually quit. In addition, players with this approach receive a sanction and pass into the second card cycle, in which they quit with a card accumulated less than in the first cycle.
It is therefore not so clear whether it really is an advantage.
Finally, such practices are not directed against the sporting spirit, which also includes strategic decisions to maximise the benefits of the rules.
In this case, the players did not want to avoid sanctions (that would actually be a clear case of circumvention), they would rather choose when they would be subjected to them.
They made a strategic decision without a penalty or fleeing from it.
Although the limit between invention and the regulatory environment is misguided, I believe that this is a clear case of invention.
I have the impression that the polemic has arisen due to two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the nature of the provoked rule transfer.
The damage to the principles of sport caused by these acts is less ethical than rather aesthetic.
