USA changes the rules for receiving a visa
Persons must present themselves to the consulate at the visa application offices before they talk; the cost of waiting is reduced.
As of 10 January 2011, the procedures for applying for a visa will change in the Embassy of the United States and in the Consulates.
In the new procedure, most applicants must present themselves in the Consulate at the visa application services (ASC, the initial letters in English).
The staff of the ASC shall record the biometric data of the applicant, which shall be verified by the consulate prior to the conversation.
The new procedure has certain advantages for the aspirants, including:
The total cost of the processing of the visa will decrease, since it is no longer necessary to pay separately the appointment, the processing of the visa application and the transport service with which the document is provided.
The applicant shall make only one single payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the countervalue of 140 dollars for a tourist visa, 150 dollars for visas with application (including visas for temporary workers) and 390 dollars for hands and investors.
Those who only want to extend their visa must not have a conversation in the consulate; they must only imagine themselves at the next ASC where they present their documents and their fingerprints.
Since biometric data are collected in the ASC, the applicants who need a second date for conversation in the consulate remain there less time than before.
Those who apply for a visa in the Consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer have to pay the 26-dollar service fee.
For more information on the new visa application procedure, see: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
