The United States National Aviation and Space Authority (NASA) announces an astrobiological discovery tomorrow, Thursday, which could confirm the theory of the existence of alien life.
The discovery will be presented tomorrow at 1 p.m. at a press conference at NASA headquarters in Washington by experts from astrobiology, which is a science that examines the origin, development, distribution and the future of life in the universe.
When convening the press conference, NASA assured that it would present "a supervisory fund for the search for alien life", which triggered speculation from experts from other countries.
The discovery could prove the theory that in hostile environments that were previously considered inhabitable, human-like creatures can exist. It was raised the hypothesis that they could become intelligent living beings - like human beings - if their living conditions improved.
Apparently it is a microbe found on the ground of the Mono Lake in the Yosemite National Park, California. It lives there in an environment that was considered too toxic for all possible forms of life, since the lake is highly arsenic.
In some way, the microbial uses arsenic as a survival resource. Taking into account this ability, the chances that there might be similar life on other planets that do not have our protective atmosphere are increased.
When these organisms metabolize the arsenic, according to the astrobiologists, "there is a real life form, a second life form that differs from the one we know."
The Space Agency announces the actual range of its findings at the press conference tomorrow, on Thursday.
The conference is attended by Geobiologist Pamela Conrad, who examines the possibility of life on Mars, and the Biologist Steven Benner, one of the scientists who studyes Titan (the largest moon Saturns) in the question of whether its chemical composition is similar to the earth.
